Dataset's Features Explanation¶

  • Administrative: Number of pages visited by the visitor about the website's administration.
  • Administrative_Duration: Total time spent by the visitor on the administrative pages.
  • Informational: Number of pages visited by the visitor that provide information about the website.
  • Informational_Duration: Total time spent by the visitor on the informational pages.
  • ProductRelated: Number of pages visited by the visitor that relate to products or services.
  • ProductRelated_Duration: Total time spent by the visitor on the product-related pages.
  • BounceRates: The percentage of visitors who leave the website after visiting only one page.
  • ExitRates: The percentage of visitors who leave the website after visiting one or more pages.
  • PageValues: Average value of the pages visited by the visitor.
  • SpecialDay: The closeness of the website visiting time to a special day (e.g. Mother's Day, Valentine's Day).
  • Month: Month of the year in which the website was visited.
  • OperatingSystems: The operating system of the visitor's computer.
  • Browser: The browser used by the visitor to access the website.
  • Region: The geographic region from which the visitor accesses the website.
  • TrafficType: Traffic source of the visitor.
  • VisitorType: Type of visitor to the website (e.g. returning or new).
  • Weekend: A binary indicator whether the visitor accessed the website during a weekend.
  • Revenue: A binary indicator of whether the visitor made a purchase on the website.

The dataset has been obtained from the UCI Machine Learning Repository, you can find the link here: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Online+Shoppers+Purchasing+Intention+Dataset

plt.figure(figsize=(15,4))
tf_false = df[df['Revenue'] == False].groupby('TrafficType').size().reset_index(name='counts')
tf_true = df[df['Revenue'] == True].groupby('TrafficType').size().reset_index(name='counts')
tf_ratio = tf_true.merge(tf_false, on='TrafficType', suffixes=('_true', '_false'))
tf_ratio['ratio'] = tf_ratio['counts_true'] / tf_ratio['counts_false']
tf_ratio = tf_ratio[tf_ratio['counts_true'] > 50]
tf_ratio = tf_ratio[tf_ratio['counts_false'] > 50]
tf_ratio = tf_ratio.sort_values(by='ratio', ascending=False)
plt.bar(tf_ratio['TrafficType'], tf_ratio['ratio'])
plt.xlabel('Traffic Type')
plt.ylabel('Revenue Ratio')
plt.show()

People who are directed to the website through Traffic Type '8' tend to make the most purchases. This suggests that advertising through this medium may be more effective.

In the dataset, there are four categorical variables present, which are Month, VisitorType, Weekend, and Revenue. Of these, Weekend and Revenue are boolean data types. To make the data suitable for modeling, these categorical data need to be transformed into numerical data.

Implementing Machine Learning techniques to transform categorical data into numerical data.¶

  • One-Hot Encoding
  • Label Encoding
In [58]:
df = pd.get_dummies(df, columns=['Month'], prefix='Month')

This code is performing one-hot encoding on the "Month" column of the dataframe "df". In this case, the "Month" column in the "df" dataframe is converted into multiple columns representing each unique category in the "Month" column. Each unique category is represented by a binary column that is either 0 or 1, with 1 representing the presence of a category and 0 representing the absence. The new columns are named with the "prefix" argument specified in the code, which is "Month_".

In [8]:
label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
df['VisitorType'] = label_encoder.fit_transform(df['VisitorType'])
df['Weekend'] = label_encoder.fit_transform(df['Weekend'])
df['Revenue'] = label_encoder.fit_transform(df['Revenue'])

In this code, three columns of the dataframe, 'VisitorType', 'Weekend', and 'Revenue' have been label-encoded. The LabelEncoder object is created and fit on each column to transform the categorical data into numerical data. The transformed data is then saved back into the respective columns in the dataframe 'df'. This process is done so that the categorical data can be used in machine learning algorithms which typically require numerical data.

Here, in this histogram, we can observe that there is a significant amount of abnormal distribution of the data.

In our dataset, we found a sizable number of outliers, especially in the features "Informational" and "Informational Duration." Therefore, We employed the Capping method, which entails defining a limit for the values regarded as outliers, to address these outliers. Then, any values outside or inside of this range are regarded as outliers. With this approach, the majority of the data can be kept while the outlier problem is still successfully resolved. But we were unable to use this strategy for the two features indicated above because doing so would leave the data with just one value.

In [18]:
def cap_outliers(df, col, threshold=1.5):
    q1, q3 = df[col].quantile([0.25, 0.75])
    iqr = q3 - q1
    upper_bound = q3 + threshold * iqr
    lower_bound = q1 - threshold * iqr
    df[col] = df[col].apply(lambda x: upper_bound if x > upper_bound else x)
    df[col] = df[col].apply(lambda x: lower_bound if x < lower_bound else x)
    return df

outliers = ['Administrative', 'Administrative_Duration', 'ProductRelated', 'ProductRelated_Duration', 'BounceRates', 'ExitRates']
for col in outliers:
    df = cap_outliers(df, col)

However, it's crucial to remember that a high accuracy score is not always a sign of a strong model; instead, performance metrics like precision, recall, F1 score, and confusion matrix should also be taken into account.Therefore, in the later stage, I have examined these performance metrics.

In this case, the precision for class 0 is 0.99 and for class 1 it is 0.93. This means that when the model predicted a value as class 0, it was correct 99% of the time, and when it predicted a value as class 1, it was correct 93% of the time. The recall of the model is calculated as the ratio of true positive predictions to the total number of actual positive cases. In this case, the recall for class 0 is 0.92 and for class 1 it is 0.99. The accuracy of the model is calculated as the ratio of correct predictions to the total number of predictions made by the model. In this case, the overall accuracy is 0.96, meaning that the model correctly predicted 96% of all the cases.

Confusion Matrix for KNN:
[[1385  677]
 [ 144 1963]]

The number of true positive, false positive, true negative, and false negative predictions made by the model are displayed in a 2x2 table known as the confusion matrix for KNN. There are 4 components in the table: The number of times the model accurately predicted the positive class is known as the true positive rate (TP). In this instance, the model accurately identified the positive class as 1963 occurrences. The number of times the model mispredicted the positive class is known as the false positive rate (FP). In this instance, the model predicted 677 occurrences as belonging to the positive class wrongly. The amount of times the model accurately predicted the negative class is known as True Negative (TN). 1385 of the instances in this instance fell into the negative class, as predicted by the model. False Negative (FN), this indicates how frequently the model predicted the negative class erroneously. In this instance, the model predicted 144 occurrences as belonging to the negative class wrongly.

The confusion matrix for XGB displays the accuracy of the model in terms of correctly predicted positive cases (TP), correctly predicted negative cases (TN), falsely predicted positive cases (FP), and falsely predicted negative cases (FN). The number of times the positive class (1) was predicted by the model and was actually present is known as True Positives (TP). In this instance, 1968 positive cases were accurately predicted by the model. False Positives (FP) are the number of times the model predicted the positive class (1) when it was really negative. 457 erroneous positive predictions were made by the model in this instance. The percentage of times the model correctly predicted the negative class (0) and it actually was negative is known as True Negatives (TN). In this instance, 1605 of the negative situations that the model predicted were accurate. False Negatives (FN) are the instances in which a class was predicted by the model to be negative (class (0)) but was really positive. 139 false negative predictions were made by the model in this situation.

Web User Interface¶

import gradio as gr

rf = RandomForestClassifier()
rf.fit(X_train, y_train)

def predict(Administrative, Administrative_Duration, Informational, Informational_Duration, ProductRelated, ProductRelated_Duration, BounceRates, ExitRates):
    input_values = [Administrative, Administrative_Duration, Informational, Informational_Duration, ProductRelated, ProductRelated_Duration, BounceRates, ExitRates]
    prediction = rf.predict([input_values])[0]
    return "Predicted Output: " + str(prediction) + "\n\nNote: 0 means negative intention of purchase and 1 means positive intention of purchase."

To sum up, the Gradio-developed online user interface offers a simple and practical platform for predicting the revenue of e-commerce websites. A machine learning model 'Random Forest' is used by the interface to anticipate whether or not the website will make money by taking into account administrative, informational, and product-related inputs. Input fields are placed in the centre of the page, and colour has been added to make the interface more aesthetically pleasing and user-friendly. With the help of this user interface, companies will be able to forecast the revenue from their websites quickly and effectively, making data-driven decisions regarding their online presence and offering insightful information for enhancing the functionality of their websites.
